Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by Chibuike Lawrence Orji-Oko¶

Introduction¶

This is an exploration of the Ford GoBike dataset. The Ford GoBike Dataset consists of information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering greater San Francisco. The data features include duration (secs) and others such as DateTime, customer type, gender, and some additional variables.

Data Cleaning¶

Issue #1: Columns with wrong data types¶

Define: Convert the columns to the appropriate data types¶

In [7]:
df['start_time'] = df['start_time'].astype('datetime64[ns]') # from object data type to datetime 
df['end_time'] = df['end_time'].astype('datetime64[ns]')     # from object data type to datetime 
df['start_station_id'] = df['start_station_id'].astype(str)  # from float data type to string (object)
df['end_station_id'] = df['end_station_id'].astype(str)      # from float data type to string (object)
df['bike_id'] = df['bike_id'].astype(str)                    # from integer data type to string (object)
df['member_gender'] = df['member_gender'].astype('category') # from string (object) data type to category
df['user_type'] = df['user_type'].astype('category')         # from string (object) data type to category

Issue #2: Replace missing values in both member_gender and member_birth_year columns¶

In [8]:
# Replace missing values in member_gender column
df['member_gender'].fillna(df['member_gender'].mode()[0], inplace=True)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 rides (rows) in the dataset with 16 features (columns). There are 2 datetime, 4 float, 2 integer, 6 string (object) and 2 categorical variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Interested in learning more about the users and what time of the day were most ride taken.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The duration, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip, start_date and end_date will provide me the information needed for this findings. We can extract the day, week, and month features from the start_date and end_date columns.

What is the distribution of member gender?¶

In [18]:
gender_order = df['member_gender'].value_counts().index
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
ax = sns.countplot(data=df, x='member_gender', color=base_color, order=gender_order)

total = len(df)
for p in ax.patches:
    percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
    x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
    y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
    ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12, ha='center')
plt.show();

Insight:¶

Most users are males. 75.74% of the users of the Ford GoBike system are males while 22.27% are females. Those that filled "other" as gender account for 1.99% of the total rides.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most of the distributions are pretty normal. The majority users are subscribers with a very high percentage of male customers as expected. The busiest hours being during the rush hour time of the day. The unusual point we have found however is the distribution of rides when we look at each day of the wek. I did not expect the busiest day to be Thursday. I extracted hour, day, and month from the start_time and end_time columns.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The customer type users spend more time on average compare to subscribers while the female gender spend slightly higher time on average than male. Also non bike share and bike share for all trip appears to be similar.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

We observed that customer type riders have little efect on the number of trips in any week day. There both male and female genders that are subscriber and customer users. Also bike-sharing service seems to be available to subscibers.

Conclusions¶

Most of the Ford GoBike users are subscribers (89.2%).

The majority of the rides are under 30 minutes.

The most busy hours are during the rush hours of a day, between the hours of 7AM and 9AM when people are going to work, and between the hours of 4PM and 6PM when people are returning back from work.

Thursdays have the hightest trips, followed by Tuedays. While weekends (Saturdays and Sundays) have the lowest rides.

Most riders are males. 75.74% of the users of the Ford GoBike system are males while 22.27% are females. Those that filled "other" as gender account for 1.99% of the total rides.

Non bike-sharing is preferred more than bike-sharing.

Customers on the average take longer trips than subscribers.

Saturday, Monday, and Sunday have the hightest trip duration compared to other days of the week.

Those who indicated "other" as their gender group travels for a longer duration for both bike sharing and non bike sharing, followed by the female group, while, the male gender are the least.

Subscribers use Ford GoBike for short distance travels while customers take longer rides.
